---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const detailingProducts = [
  {
    name: "Meguiar's Gold Class Car Wash",
    priceTier: "$10 - $15",
    type: "Foam Cannon/Bucket",
    keyFeature: "Safe on Wax",
    bestFor: "Enthusiasts wanting rich suds and safe cleaning",
    pros: ["Rich lather", "Conditioners enhance shine", "Ph balanced"],
    cons: ["Not the cheapest per ounce", "Requires good rinsing"],
  },
  {
    name: "Chemical Guys Mr. Pink",
    priceTier: "$8 - $12",
    type: "Foam Cannon",
    keyFeature: "High Suds",
    bestFor: "Maximum foam cannon output",
    pros: ["Extreme suds", "Slick feel", "Pleasant scent"],
    cons: ["Can strip some weak waxes if used heavy", "Thick consistency"],
  },
  {
    name: "Adam's Polishes Detail Spray",
    priceTier: "$12 - $18",
    type: "Spray",
    keyFeature: "High Gloss",
    bestFor: "Quick touch-ups and drying aid",
    pros: ["Incredible scent", "Adds great slickness", "Versatile"],
    cons: ["Pricey for frequent use", "Not a replacement for proper wax"],
  },
  {
    name: "Griot's Garage Best of Show Wax",
    priceTier: "$20 - $25",
    type: "Liquid/Paste",
    keyFeature: "Deep Glow",
    bestFor: "Show cars and dark paint",
    pros: ["Deep, warm glow", "Easy to apply", "Smells great"],
    cons: ["Durability is lower than sealants", "Requires more effort to remove than modern sprays"],
  }
];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What is the two-bucket wash method?",
    a: "The two-bucket method uses one bucket for soapy water and another with clean water for rinsing your wash mitt. This prevents dirt from being reintroduced to the paint, minimizing swirl marks."
  },
  {
    q: "When should I use a clay bar?",
    a: "Use a clay bar after washing when the paint feels rough to the touch. It removes embedded contaminants like rail dust and tree sap that washing alone can't remove, preparing the surface for polishing or waxing."
  },
  {
    q: "What is the difference between polish, wax, sealant, and ceramic coating?",
    a: "Polish removes microscopic scratches and refines the finish. Wax provides a warm glow and short-term protection (1-3 months). Sealants offer synthetic protection for 3-6 months. Ceramic coatings bond to the paint for durable protection lasting 1-5+ years."
  },
  {
    q: "How do I care for leather interiors?",
    a: "Clean leather with a dedicated pH-balanced leather cleaner and a soft brush. Follow up with a leather conditioner or protector to keep the material supple and prevent cracking from UV damage."
  },
  {
    q: "Is DIY detailing worth it compared to professional services?",
    a: "DIY detailing saves money long-term but requires an initial investment in tools (buckets, towels, DA polisher) and time. Professional details offer convenience and expertise, especially for complex paint correction or ceramic coating applications."
  }
];

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article"
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": faqs.map(f => ({
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": f.q,
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": f.a
      }
    }))
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout
  site="pleasestartplease"
  title="Complete Car Detailing Guide"
  description="Learn the best car detailing techniques, from the two-bucket wash and clay bar to paint correction and interior care. Discover top products from Meguiar's, Chemical Guys, Adam's, and Griot's."
  canonical="https://pleasestartplease.photonbuilder.com/car-detailing-guide"
  schema={JSON.stringify(schema)}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Complete Car Detailing Guide</h1>
      <p>Master the art of car detailing. From the perfect wash technique to advanced paint correction and interior care.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Detailing your car goes beyond a simple wash. It's about preserving the value, protecting the finish, and achieving a show-room shine. This guide covers the essential steps, tools, and products you need.</p>

      <h2>The Wash Technique</h2>
      <p>The foundation of detailing is a safe wash. Always use the two-bucket method: one bucket for soapy water, one for rinsing your mitt. This prevents dirt from causing swirl marks. A foam cannon is excellent for pre-soaking to lift heavy dirt before touching the paint.</p>

      <h2>Decontamination: The Clay Bar Process</h2>
      <p>After washing, if your paint feels rough, it needs decontamination. A clay bar (used with a lubricant) glides over the paint, pulling out embedded iron particles, sap, and industrial fallout, leaving the surface glass-smooth.</p>

      <h2>Paint Correction Basics</h2>
      <p>Paint correction involves using a Dual Action (DA) polisher with abrasive compounds and polishes to permanently remove swirl marks and scratches, restoring true clarity to the clear coat.</p>

      <h2>Protection: Polish vs Wax vs Sealant vs Ceramic Coating</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Polish: Abrasive liquid used to remove defects. Does not protect.</li>
        <li>Wax: Natural carnauba. Deep glow, lasts 1-3 months.</li>
        <li>Sealant: Synthetic polymers. High gloss, lasts 3-6 months.</li>
        <li>Ceramic Coating: Liquid polymer that chemically bonds to paint. Extreme durability (years) and hydrophobics.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Interior Detailing</h2>
      <p>For leather care, use pH-neutral cleaners and follow with conditioners to prevent cracking. For fabric cleaning, vacuum thoroughly, spot treat stains, and use an extractor for deep cleaning. Protect your dashboard with UV-blocking dressings (avoid greasy finishes).</p>

      <h2>Wheel and Tire Care</h2>
      <p>Clean wheels first to avoid splashing brake dust onto clean paint. Use dedicated, non-acidic wheel cleaners and separate brushes. Finish tires with a water-based dressing for a clean, satin look that won't sling onto the paint.</p>

      <h2>Seasonal Detailing Schedule</h2>
      <p>A good schedule: Full decontamination and seal in Spring and Fall. Regular maintenance washes every 1-2 weeks. Interior wipe-downs monthly.</p>

      <h2>DIY vs Professional Detail Costs</h2>
      <p>DIY requires an upfront investment ($100-$300 for basic tools) but saves money per wash. Professional details range from $150 for basic services to $1,000+ for multi-stage paint correction and ceramic coatings, offering expertise and convenience.</p>

      <h2>Comparison Table</h2>
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Product</th>
              <th>Price Tier</th>
              <th>Type</th>
              <th>Key Feature</th>
              <th>Best For</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {detailingProducts.map(prod => (
              <tr>
                <td>{prod.name}</td>
                <td>{prod.priceTier}</td>
                <td>{prod.type}</td>
                <td>{prod.keyFeature}</td>
                <td>{prod.bestFor}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Detailed Reviews</h2>
      {detailingProducts.map((prod, i) => (
        <div class="review-card">
          <div class="review-header">
            <div>
              <span class="review-rank">#{i + 1}</span>
              <h3>{prod.name}</h3>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="pros-cons">
            <div class="pros">
              <h4>Pros</h4>
              <ul>{prod.pros.map(p => <li>{p}</li>)}</ul>
            </div>
            <div class="cons">
              <h4>Cons</h4>
              <ul>{prod.cons.map(c => <li>{c}</li>)}</ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      {faqs.map(f => (
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>{f.q}</h3>
          <p>{f.a}</p>
        </div>
      ))}

    </section>
  </div>

  <style>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    /* Comparison Table */
    .table-wrapper { overflow-x: auto; margin: 1.5rem 0; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>